<TITLE> France says position unchanged on Iran sanctions </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Dec 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - France said on Tuesday it would continue to press for UN sanctions against Iran despite a US intelligence report that said Tehran had halted its nuclear weapons programme. The US National Intelligence Estimate (NIE) report released on Monday took US friends and foes by surprise after years of strident rhetoric from Washington accusing Iran of pursuing a covert nuclear weapons programme. Analysts said the report -- which said Tehran had halted its nuclear weapons programme in 2003 -- might undermine Washington's drive to persuade other world powers to agree further UN sanctions against the Islamic Republic. "Our position remains unchanged," Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Pascale Andreani told a regular news conference. "It appears that Iran is not respecting its international obligations." "We must keep up the pressure on Iran ... We will continue to work on the introduction of restrictive measures in the framework of the United Nations," she added. Andreani said the five permanent members of the UN Security Council and Germany had reacted to facts as they had been reported by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) in imposing two rounds of sanctions against Tehran. IAEA reports had shown that Tehran had not answered all outstanding questions about its nuclear activities and continued to try to master uranium enrichment, she sa
